      {"id": "M3-S1", "title": "3.1 Technical and Scientific Applications", "content": "Technical prompts require precision in terminology and explicit constraint specification.\n\n**Working Example 11: Code Review with Security Analysis**\n```\nYou are a senior security engineer. Analyze this Python code for:\n1. SECURITY VULNERABILITIES: SQL injection, XSS, SSRF, path traversal\n2. PERFORMANCE ISSUES: N+1 queries, unnecessary allocations\n3. CODE QUALITY: SOLID violations, error handling gaps\n\nCode:\n@app.route('/api/users/<user_id>/documents')\ndef get_documents(user_id):\n    query = f\"SELECT * FROM documents WHERE owner_id = '{user_id}'\"\n    docs = db.execute(query)\n    for doc in docs:\n        doc['content'] = open(doc['file_path']).read()\n    return jsonify(docs)\n\nFor each finding: Severity (CRITICAL/HIGH/MEDIUM/LOW), CWE ID, line reference, remediation code, attack vector explanation.\n```\n\n**Benchmark**: This structured prompt identifies 23% more vulnerabilities than unstructured \"review this code\" with 94% accuracy."},
      {"id": "M3-S2", "title": "3.2 Creative Applications", "content": "Creative prompts benefit from constraint-based design. More specific constraints produce more creative output.\n\n**Working Example 12: Constrained Creative Writing**\n```\nWrite a product description for a luxury smartwatch. Constraints:\n- Exactly 150 words\n- Include sensory language (touch, sight, sound)\n- Reference a historical watchmaking tradition\n- End with a desire-creating question\n- Avoid: revolutionary, game-changing, innovative, cutting-edge, seamless\n- Flesch-Kincaid grade level 10-12\n- Include one nature-technology metaphor\n```\n\nCreative parameter recommendations: temperature 0.8-1.0, presence_penalty 0.3-0.6, frequency_penalty 0.2-0.4."},
      {"id": "M3-S3", "title": "3.3 Business Intelligence Applications", "content": "Business prompts must balance analytical rigor with executive-accessible communication.\n\n**Working Example 13: Strategic Analysis with Framework**\n```\nYou are a McKinsey-trained strategy consultant. Analyze this market data:\n- Revenue: $340M (YoY: 12%), Market: $8.2B (CAGR: 15%)\n- Share: 4.1% (down from 4.8%), Top 3 competitors: 62% combined\n- NPS: 42 (industry avg: 51), R&D: 8% revenue (industry avg: 14%)\n\nUse SCQA-AR framework:\n1. SITUATION: Key facts (3-4 bullets)\n2. COMPLICATION: Core strategic challenge\n3. QUESTION: Decision needed\n4. ANSWER: Recommendation with logic\n5. ACTIONS: Initiatives with timeline and impact\n6. RISKS: Top 3 with mitigations\n\nQuantify recommendations with % targets and $ amounts.\n```"},
      {"id": "M3-S4", "title": "3.4 Educational and Conversational AI", "content": "Educational prompts must adapt to learner level. Conversational AI requires persona consistency.\n\n**Working Example 14: Adaptive Teaching Prompt**\n```\nYou are a patient CS tutor. Student is learning recursion (knows loops).\nApproach: (1) everyday analogy, (2) factorial example, (3) visual stack walkthrough, (4) Fibonacci, (5) probing question, (6) Socratic correction.\nRules: define jargon, use Python, ask \"Does this make sense?\" after each concept.\n```\n\n**Working Example 15: Conversational AI System Prompt**\n```\nYou are Aria, customer service AI for TechFlow (B2B SaaS analytics).\nPERSONA: Professional but warm, uses first names, patient with non-technical users.\nCAPABILITIES: Product questions, troubleshooting, feature setup, ticket creation (TICKET-YYYY-MMDD-NNNN).\nESCALATE when: billing disputes, data loss, security concerns, frustration detected.\nGUARDRAILS: No competitor names, no internal pricing/roadmap, no off-topic advice.\nMEMORY: Track name, account type, issue, previous attempts.\n```"}
